context: From about 1800 a fresh influx of <a0_0><b5_0>Greek architectural<a0_0/> examples, seen through the medium of etchings and engravings,<b5_0/> gave a new impetus to neoclassicism, the <a1_0><b8_0>Greek Revival<b8_0/><a1_0/>. There was little to no <b6_0>direct knowledge of Greek civilization<b6_0/> before the middle of the <a2_0>18th century<a2_0/> in Western Europe, when an expedition funded by the Society of Dilettanti in 1751 and led by <a3_0>James Stuart and Nicholas Revett<a3_0/> began serious archaeological enquiry. Stuart was commissioned after his return from Greece by George Lyttelton to produce <b7_0>the first Greek building in England<b7_0/>, the <a4_0>garden temple at <b9_0>Hagley Hall<b9_0/> (1758–59)<a4_0/>. A number of British architects in the second half of the century took up the expressive challenge of the Doric from their aristocratic patrons, including Joseph Bonomi and John Soane, but it was to remain the private enthusiasm of connoisseurs up to the first decade of the 19th century.
